<h1>Travel info</h1>

<br />
<p>

<b>Stockholm is the capital of and the biggest city in Sweden. As such, it is the main hub of transportation in the country. I.e., it is easy coming here, whether by air, sea, train, bus or car.</b></p>

<br/><br/>
<h2>Hotel</h2>

<p>If you want to book your accommodations, you can use this <a href="http://www.hotellsverige.se/Engindex.htm" onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">hotel guide</a> or <a href="http://www.stfturist.se/templates/MapSearch.aspx?id=5095" onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">this youth hostel directory</a>.</p>

<br/><br/>
<h2>Air</h2>

<p>There are two international airports in Stockholm. Arlanda is the biggest, and it is located about 60 km north of the city. There is a high-speed train (<a href="http://www.arlandaexpress.com/AtrainHTML/smpage.fwx?page=432" onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">"Arlandabanan</a>") going to the city. It costs 190 SEK, and takes about 20 minutes. There are also not so fast, but cheaper, buses from <a href="http://www.peopletravel.se/en/koncernen" onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">Flygbussarna</a> going the same way. They cost 90&nbsp;SEK. A taxi takes about 30-40 minutes and costs about 400&nbsp;SEK.
<br/><br/>
The other international airport, Bromma, is located much closer to the city center, and a taxi to the center would take about 10-15 minutes and cost about 150-200&nbsp;SEK. Also, <a href="http://www.peopletravel.se/en/koncernen"  onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">Flygbussarna</a> have buses going from Bromma to the city center. Bromma is a quite small airport, and only short-distance flights from northern Europe arrives here.</p>
<br/><br/>

<p>Low-cost airlines have flights arriving at Västerås and Skavsta airports. These airports are more than 100&nbsp;km away from Stockholm, but you can travel to Stockholm with the <a href="http://www.sj.se/sj/jsp/polopoly.jsp?d=10&amp;l=en" onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">SJ</a> trains or <a href="http://www.peopletravel.se/en/koncernen"  onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">Flygbussarna</a> buses.</p>

<br/><br/>
<h2>Sea</h2>

<p>If you're coming from the east (Finland, Balticum, Russia etc), the easiest and most comfortable way to get here is to travel on one of the party ferries crossing the Baltic Sea. There are ferries going to Stockholm from Turkku, Helsinki, Tallin, Riga, Klaipeda and St. Petersburg. Ferry operators include <a href="http://www.birkacruises.com/site.aspx?id=240" onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">Birka Cruises</a>, <a href="http://www.vikingline.fi/index.asp?lang=en" onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">Viking Line</a>, <a href="http://www.tallink.fi/en/index.html" onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">Tallink</a> and <a href="http://www.silja.com/" onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">Silja Line</a>.</p>

<br/><br/>
<h2>Bus</h2>

<p>There are buses in regular traffic from most cities in Sweden and from major cities in the surrounding countries. Bus operators include <a href="http://www.swebusexpress.se/"  onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">Swebus Express</a>, <a href="http://www.safflebussen.se/" onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">Säfflebussen</a> (in Swedish or German) and <a href="http://www.eurolines-travel.com/" onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">Eurolines</a>.</p>

<br/><br/>
<h2>Train</h2>

<p>There are trains going to Stockholm from all major cities in Europe. Check out <a href="http://www.sj.se/sj/jsp/polopoly.jsp?d=10&amp;l=en"  onclick="window.open(this.href); return false">SJ</a> or your favourite train operator.</p>

<br/><br/>
<h2>Car</h2>
<p>The European highways E4, E18 and E20 goes through Stockholm.</p>

